description:
Perfectly situated in one of the most culturally vibrant yet tranquil neighborhoods of Manhattan, this lovingly designed flat has unique details like custom built furniture, antique prints, and handmade Finnish/Japanese housewares. Only a few minutes walk to the High Line, Whitney Museum,  Hudson River parks, Chelsea Market, countless renowned restaurants, and fashion boutiques.

Please do not submit any reservation request until you have first written to me AND I have written back to you to CONFIRM the availability. 

Any reservation request sent that has not first had the availability confirmed will be declined. Thank you!

--------------------------------------------------------------------

If you are looking for an authentic New Yorker experience and have a discerning eye for design and character, this might be your perfect home away from home...

From its custom designed furniture to its numerous framed art works and handmade ceramics, everything in this apartment has been specially chosen for this apartment. Every detail has been lovingly considered. 

The beautifully sunlit main living area is the most spacious and complexly ornamented. A bright bedroom, simple shower-bath restroom, and kitchen niche sit adjacent to this space.

Please realize that this 1 bedroom apartment is on the 3rd floor of an 1880s "walkup" which means there is no elevator, only stairs.

The West Village is one of the oldest and most charming neighborhoods in all of Manhattan. Its non-perpendicular streets, old paving stone roads, and 18th-19th century buildings give the neighborhood a distinctly old word feel that you will not find anywhere else in the city. But there is nothing old or tired about the West Village. In fact, the neighborhood boasts one of the city's highest concentrations of good restaurants, charming cafes, and designer fashion boutiques. Unlike the touristic bustle and chaotic rudeness of Midtown, the West Village's tree lined streets give a calming atmosphere where people love to dwell and talk to neighbors. Because of its singular nature, the West Village has attracted a large concentration of well known writers, actors, musicians and other successful artists as residents throughout the years...

As with the rest of Manhattan the best ways to get around in the West Village besides walking or biking are — Taxi, Uber and of course, the Subway. 

The stations closest to the apartment are:

Christopher St / Sheridan Square Station
1, 2 trains

14th St / 8th Ave Station
A, C, E trains
L train

West 4th St Station
A, C, E trains
B, D, F, M trains

Since this is a personal residence (and not just a rental) there are objects of value in the house of the type that you might not encounter in a typical, full-time Air BnB rental. Please feel free to examine our books and magazines, but remember to treat these and all other objects with great care, just as if you were staying at a best friend or family member's home. Anything that it stored away in closets (e.g. suits, dresses) or filing cabinets, we kindly ask that you refrain from accessing.

hosts.about:
I am a 37 year old an art director, game designer, an architect based in New York City. 

I have lived and worked in ten countries and visited many more. I sustain friendships with all types of people, from scientists and soldiers to musicians and artists. It is very important to me that I understand all different views and walks of life. 

Besides my career in design, I am a fan of all things epicurean, particularly food and drink. Both dense urban fabrics and pristine nature are inspiring to me.

photos.caption: Designed and lived in by a media producer and architect, this cozy 1880s walkup in Manhattan's West Village has been lovingly renovated to make maximum use of space and provide a calming atmosphere.
Tranquil blues and earth tones make lounging on this living room sofa truly relaxing.
This custom-designed kitchen island doubles as a kitchen prep counter and dining table with bar stools. Handmade Japanese ceramics and Finnish glassware compliment the color palette of the interior.
Opposite view to the kitchen niche and bathroom...

The kitchen niche includes an efficiency size, 4 burner gas range and oven, sink, and new Frigidare refrigerator plus freezer. Counter space is small here which is why we built our island which can be used as both a prep counter and for dining.
Bauhaus prints, 19th century ethnographic engravings, cartography, as well as the owner's personal architectural drawings and photographs adorn the wall.
A dimmable maple veneer lantern and Edison bulb pendant provide romantic illumination alongside candle lit lamps during the evening.

Small but well lit, the bedroom comes with a Full-sized bed and mattress by the Japanese company, MUJI. Sleep soundly on down stuffed pillows with high thread count Egyptian cotton sheets in the summer; cozy flannel sheets in the winter. AC unit sits in the window during the hottest summer months...
Basic toilet and shower-bath. Clean, white, and basic. (Haven't quite gotten around to making this an 80s fashion photo inspired, neon trip... but that's definitely next.)
View from all three of the apartment's windows—the studio and event space of an iconic NYC fashion designer.
The Elk Coffeeshop (downstairs)
Christopher Street Pier (2 min walking)
The Spotted Pig (3 min walking)
The Rusty Knot Bar (3 min walking)
High Line Park (5 min walking)
Whitney Museum (5 min walking)
100+ private art galleries in Chelsea (10 min walking)
Chelsea Market (10 min walking)
Washington Square Park (12 min walking)
Union Square Greenmarkets (on weekend, 18 min walking)
Little Branch Speakeasy (6 min walking)
